title: Zelensky, Citing Equipment Gaps, Says It’s Too Soon for Counteroffensive
description: Ukraine’s president played down the chance of an imminent military move, but the claim was greeted with some skepticism.

title: Sudan’s Clashing Forces Agree to Allow Aid In, but Not to a Truce, U.S. Says
description: Officials hope the agreement will allow the delivery of life-saving aid and ease conditions for the millions of Sudanese suffering after nearly four weeks of fighting between rival generals.

title: Karl Jenkins Sets the Record Straight: He Is Not Meghan Markle
description: Online jokesters claimed that Karl Jenkins was the Duchess of Sussex in disguise at the coronation. He sets the record straight.

title: Kemal Dervis, Who Eased Turkey’s Economic Crisis, Dies at 74
description: Changes he spearheaded in 2001 helped avert disaster. He later led the United Nations Development Program.

title: Days After Crowning the King, Archbishop Condemns U.K. Migrant Plan
description: The Most Rev. Justin Welby, the archbishop of Canterbury and a member of the House of Lords, told Parliament that the government’s plan to deal with immigration is “morally unacceptable.”

title: Your Friday Briefing: A Guide to the Thai Elections
description: Today, our Southeast Asia bureau chief explains what’s at stake in the Thai election. Also, a court in Pakistan ordered the release of Imran Khan.

title: K-Pop Stars BTS Will Release a Book Telling Their Own Story in July
description: The announcement by their U.S. publisher, Flatiron Books, came after days of frantic speculation by their fervent fans.

title: What Song Represents Your Home?
description: Tell us why it evokes the spirit of the place where you live.

title: W.H.O. Ends Mpox Global Emergency
description: The virus was contained in most countries with a combination of vaccination and behavioral change.

title: Officials Seek to Avert Border Chaos as U.S. Ends Covid Policy: Live Updates
description: Border crossings have increased as people attempt to enter the United States ahead of the lifting of Title 42, which allowed agents to swiftly remove migrants on public health grounds.

title: Erdogan’s Election Prospects Take a Hit as a Challenger Drops Out
description: With Turks going to the polls on Sunday, President Recep Tayyip Erdogan had hoped for a swift victory. But the departure of one challenger is likely to benefit his main competitor.

title: Top U.S. Official Accused South Africa of Providing Weapons to Russia
description: The American ambassador to South Africa told reporters that Washington is confident a Russian ship picked up a load of weapons and ammunition near Cape Town in December.

title: D.O.E.’s Loan Program Has a Lot More Climate Capital to Give
description: Jigar Shah’s federal agency suddenly has a gusher of money to lend before the next election.

title: What to Know About Prince Harry’s Lawsuits Against the British Tabloids
description: Harry, the Duke of Sussex, has three ongoing lawsuits against newspapers. One of the cases went to trial this week and involves accusations of phone hacking.

title: Pakistan’s Supreme Court Orders Release of Imran Khan
description: The former prime minister’s arrest this week in connection with a corruption case was met with protests across Pakistan.

title: UK Says It Is Donating Long-Range ‘Storm Shadow’ Missiles to Ukraine
description: The missiles, which are launched from the air, are the latest in a pipeline of military aid delivered to the country by Britain, the United States and other NATO allies.

title: Yellen Calls Invoking 14th Amendment to Raise Debt Limit ‘Legally Questionable’
description: The Treasury secretary warned that a default would lead to a “very substantial downturn.”

title: Bank of England Raises Interest Rates to 4.5%, Highest Level in 15 Years
description: The central bank lifted its benchmark rate a quarter point, to 4.5 percent, as part of its aggressive policy to tame inflation, which has remained stubbornly high.

title: Amid Cease-Fire Talks, Hostilities Across Gaza Border Enter 3rd Day
description: After the militant organization Islamic Jihad fired hundreds of projectiles at Israel, Israeli forces said that they had killed the commander of the group’s rocket unit in an overnight strike.

title: Abortion Access Keeps Winning Elections
description: But advocates can’t agree on a strategy to hold more ballot initiatives.

title: Interpol Asks for Help in Identifying 22 Murdered Women
description: Their bodies were found over the years in Belgium, Germany and the Netherlands. A new campaign aims to find out who they were.

title: How Ana Ros, One of the World’s Best Chefs, Put Slovenia on the Culinary Map
description: Ana Ros broke through the boys’ club of fine dining, earning Hisa Franko in Slovenia two Michelin stars and a spot on the list of the world’s best restaurants.

title: Luxury Imports to Russia Take a Detour Around Sanctions — Through Dubai
description: More than a year into Vladimir Putin’s invasion, the web of global trade has adjusted to Western sanctions, with a network of middlemen sending cars, electronics and more to Russia.

title: What’s Driving Record Levels of Migration to the U.S. Border?
description: The United States is trying to curtail border crossings as a Covid-era immigration policy lifts this week, but it has little control over the crises in Latin America that have upended the lives of millions.

title: E.P.A. Proposes First Limits on Climate Pollution From Existing Power Plants
description: It’s the last in a string of major regulations proposed by the Biden administration to sharply cut the greenhouse gases produced by the United States.

title: Suspect in Natalee Holloway Disappearance to Face U.S. Charges
description: Joran van der Sloot has been a suspect in the disappearance of the teenager, Natalee Holloway, in 2005.
